  <math name="ans1">(0,2)union(5,8)</math>
  <math name="ans2">(2,4)union(5,8)</math>
  <math name="ans3" simplify>(2,4+$a),(5,4+$a)</math>
</setup>

<p>
  Use the given graph of the function <m>f</m> to answer the following questions.
</p>

<figure suppressFigureNameInCaption>
  <graph
    width="400"
    height="400"
    xmin="-1"
    xmax="8"
    ymin="-1"
    ymax="8"
    >
    <curve><function formula="3*(x-1)^2+3+$a" domain="(0,1)" /></curve>
    <curve><function formula="(x-1)^2+3+$a" domain="(1,2)" /></curve>
    <curve><function formula="-(x-3)^2+5+$a" domain="(2,3)" /></curve>
    <curve><function formula="-3*(x-3)^2+5+$a" domain="(3,4)" /></curve>
    <curve><function formula="-2*(x-5)^2+4+$a" domain="(4,5)" /></curve>
    <curve><function formula="(2/9)*(x-5)^2+4+$a" domain="(5,8)" /></curve>
  </graph>
</figure>

<p>
  <row>
    1.
    Find the largest \emph{open} interval(s) on which <m>f</m> is concave upward.
    If there is more than one interval, write your answer as a union of the intervals.
  </row>

  <row>
    Answer (in interval notation):
    <answer><award>$ans1</award></answer>
  </row>
</p>

<p>
  <row>
    2.
    Find the largest \emph{open} interval(s) on which <m>f</m> is concave downward.
    If there is more than one interval, write your answer as a union of the intervals.
  </row>

  <row>
    Answer (in interval notation):
    <answer><award>$ans2</award></answer>
  </row>
</p>

<p>
  <row>
    3.
    Find the coordinates of the points of inflection.
    List your answers as points in the form <m>(a,b)</m>.
  </row>

  <row>
    Answer (separate by commas):
    <answer><award unorderedCompare>$ans3</award></answer>
  </row>
</p>

<solution>
  <row>1: <m>$ans1</m></row>
  <row>2: <m>$ans2</m></row>
  <row>3: <m>$ans3</m></row>
</solution>
